The random intercept models are super flexible, and allow you to easily add crossed effects (for example if you also have different raters or different batches (also a different rater really)), or specify a three-level model when some of the variation between subjects is better described as variation between subjects in different countries.[^40] You can then decide to include these other variance components in the (de)nominator of your ICC calculation or not depending on whether you consider it as nuisance variance. 

::: {.callout-note title="Adjusted and consistency ICCs"}
Agreement ICCs measure the agreement in absolute  measurements, while consistency ICCs measure the agreement in relative measurements, (i.e. adjusted for the difference in means between the measurement occasions). Adjusted ICCs are used when we want to adjust for (both fixed and random) other factors (e.g. batch effects in biomarker assays). Adjusted ICCs can be interpreted as the ICC given that the level of that factor is known. This implicitly assumes that the ICC is constant for all values of this factor. Conditional ICCs, on the other hand, change with levels of a factor and give you an estimate of the ICC at a certain value of a fixed factor (@nakagawaRepeatabilityGaussianNonGaussian2010).

Predictors linked to individual measurements -- such as sampling time of day -- typically increase ICC estimates by reducing residual (within-subject) variance. In contrast, predictors that (mostly) vary between individuals -- such as smoking status -- tend to decrease both agreement and adjusted repeatability, as they absorb between-subject variance that would otherwise contribute to the numerator in the ICC calculation (@gelman2007data).
:::

[^40]: You can even add a random slope, but it gets very [complicated](https://stats.stackexchange.com/questions/115526/intraclass-correlation-coefficient-in-mixed-model-with-random-slopes/318418#318418) then as the variance depends on at what value you evaluate the random slope. 

We can also fit a Bayesian model and thereby get the uncertainty on the ICC parameters for free (also notice how fast `brms` and `STAN` are here):


